The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Larsen posts 32% rise in profit
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Larsen posts 32% rise in profit
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                           L amp;T chief finance officer Y.M. Deosthalee (centre) with general manager A.K. Mondal (right) and senior vice-president (finance) R. Shankar Raman in Mumbai on Monday. (PTI)                                  
	Mumbai, Oct. 18: Larsen amp; Toubro (L amp;T) today posted a 32 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 764.98 crore for the second quarter ended September 30 against Rs 580.40 crore in the corresponding year-ago period.         
	Analysts had estimated L amp;T to post a net profit of around Rs 650 crore.         
	The engineering and construction firm has registered an 18 per cent growth in gross sales at Rs 9,342 crore over the year-ago period because of an 11 per cent growth in order inflow.         
	This translates into a growth of 29 per cent in order inflow in the first half of this year. As of September 30, the order book stood at Rs 1,153,93 crore.         
	According to L amp;T, the execution of its engineering and construction projects had picked up during the quarter. The segment achieved sales of Rs 7,861 crore, recording an 18 per cent growth. The order inflow  including some valuable power and infrastructure projects  stood at Rs 18,880 crore. There was also an improvement in margins.         
	The better-than-expected numbers saw the L amp;T shares staging a smart turnaround on the bourses today.         
	On the BSE, the scrip hit a low of Rs 1,928.80 after opening at Rs 1,995. It ended at Rs 2,013.15, a gain of Rs 23.70 over the previous close.        
	HDFC net        
	Housing Development Finance Corporation Ltd (HDFC) today beat analyst estimates by posting a 22 per cent rise in net profit on the back of higher demand for loans. HDFC recorded a net profit of Rs 807.54 crore against Rs 663.94 crore in the year-ago period.         
	Analysts had expected the lender to report a net profit of around Rs 780 crore. Better loan offtake and reduced interest costs saw HDFCs net interest income grow 26 per cent to Rs 1,189 crore from Rs 947.03 crore in the corresponding period last year.         
	For the half year ended September, HDFC posted a 22 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 1,502.13 crore against Rs 1,128.86 crore last year. Net interest income stood at Rs 2,266.54 crore against Rs 1,777.12 crore in the previous year.         
	HDFC said lending operations for the six-month period was good with approvals growing at 29 per cent and disbursements growing 27 per cent compared with the year-ago period.         
	The HDFC scrip fell to an intra-day low of Rs 705.55 after opening strong at Rs 732 on the BSE. It ended the day at Rs 724.40, down 0.34 per cent from its previous close of Rs 726.80. The retail business, HDFC said, was robust with approvals growing 49 per cent and disbursements rising 42 per cent compared with the previous year.                                                                                                                                       
